The Greek words for pitch, τόσις and τόνος, are of course connected with the idea of stretching. It would be observed from stringed instrumente that increase in the tension pro- duoed a heightening of the piteh (ἐπίτασις), and that relaxa· tion produced a lowering (ἄνεσις). Height of piteh or high pitch is expressed by ὀξύτης, the reverse by βαρύτηςς ὀξύς and βαρύς are the words for acute and grave.

A rigorous definition of piteh does not seem to have been attempted in the ancient works on musical science. It was usual to detine the term either by means of ὀξύτης and βαρύ. της, or by means of ἐπίτασις and ἄνεσις. In the former method the idea of height and depth in pitch was assumed and pitch itself was defined as that which is common to these. This is the course puisued by Claudius Ptolemy, the Alexan- drian mathematiciau, astronomer, and geographer.

Ptolemy, Harmonice, 1. iv„ p. 8Wallis: ὀ γὰρ οὕτω λεηό- μενος τόνος κοινὸν ἂν εἴη «γένος τῆς ὀξύτητος καὶ τῆς βαρύτη- τος, παρ’ ἓν εἶδος τὸ τῆς τάσεως εἰλημμένος, ὡς τὸ πέρας τοῦ τέλους καὶ τῆς ἀρχῆς. As ‘limit' covers both ‘end’ and ‘beginning' so τόνος both ὀξύτης and βαρύτης.2

In the other method of defining piteh, the changes in pitch observed in the tenes of the humen voice and in those of musical instrumente produced the concept of an upward and downward motion, and pitch was defined as the absence of such motion, that is,asstanding or rest. This is the method
